# EtherChannel (LACP & PAgP) + ROAS Lab

## Objective
Configure Layer 2 EtherChannel using both LACP and PAgP between switches and implement Router-on-a-Stick (ROAS) for inter-VLAN routing with DHCP.

This lab is slightly modified from the original setup by replacing the L3 switch with a Layer 3 router.

## Requirements
- 4 × Cisco L2 IOU Switches  
- 1 × Cisco L3 Router  
- VPCs (end hosts as per topology)  

## Lab Overview
- Configure EtherChannel between switches using:
  - LACP (IEEE standard)
  - PAgP (Cisco proprietary)
- Connect a router to the switch
- Configure sub-interfaces on the router (ROAS)
- Configure DHCP on the router
- Ensure hosts receive IP dynamically and communicate across VLANs

## Topology
Refer to the **lab topology PNG** available in this folder.

## What You Will Do
- Configure Layer 2 EtherChannel between A-Switch1 and B-Switch1 using LACP  
- Configure Layer 2 EtherChannel between A-Switch2 and B-Switch2 using PAgP  
- Configure trunk links where required  
- Configure ROAS (sub-interfaces) on the router  
- Configure DHCP server on the router  
- Verify VLAN connectivity across EtherChannel links  
- Check load balancing method on each EtherChannel  

## Expected Outcome
- EtherChannels are successfully formed (LACP & PAgP)  
- VLAN traffic is correctly forwarded across aggregated links  
- End hosts receive IP addresses via DHCP  
- Inter-VLAN communication works through the router  
- EtherChannel load balancing is verified  

## Lab Files
- IOU images are available in the Google Drive link  
- Follow the setup guide to import images into PNETLab  
- Import the `.unl` file to load the lab topology  

## Note
- This lab replaces the L3 switch with a router using ROAS  
- Refer to the topology PNG and objective PNG for detailed guidance  
